On the morning of February 29, the U.S. Department of Health confirmed the death of a west coast patient with new coronary pneumonia in Washington state, the first officially reported death in the United States. U.S. President Donald Trump said at a White House news conference that day that the COVID-19 has confirmed 22 cases and may increase the number of cases, and he is considering whether to take further preventive and restrictive measures to reduce the spread of the virus.

Of the 22 confirmed cases of COVID-19 in the US, four are "very sick" and 15 have fully recovered or are in remission. Vice President Michel Pensée, who has just been appointed by Donald Trump to head the COVID-19's epidemic prevention and control efforts, also announced at a news conference that the U.S. government will expand its entry restrictions on Iran in view of the spread of the epidemic, any foreigner who has visited Iran in the past 14 days is prohibited from entering the country. The United States also raised its travel warnings for American citizens to Italy and South Korea to the highest level: "Do not travel. ". Two first cases in Washington state

More than a month ago, the first case of new pneumonia in the United States emerged in Washington state, where a 30-year-old male resident became ill after returning to the United States from Wuhan, China.

On Saturday, Feb. 29, a man in his late 60s died of new coronary pneumonia, the first death from the disease in the United States. There were reports that the man was at high medical risk. Redfield, director of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, said there was no evidence that the man's illness was related to travel.

A spokesman for Evergreen Health Medical Center in the suburb of Kirkland, Seattle, said the resident died at their hospital. In a statement, the Medical Center said that the COVID-19 patients who died in the state "suffered from severe respiratory disease" when they went to hospital. The center admitted two patients who tested positive for COVID-19. Another surviving patient "is being quarantined, placed and continues to receive appropriate treatment. ".

"We are dealing with an urgent and evolving situation, " Washington State Health Department official Amy Reynolds told the Associated Press.

Neither of them has traveled abroad recently.

Many of the people in the Care Center are suffering from respiratory system, making it difficult to confirm the number of infections. At present, 27 out of 108 persons under care have reported suspected symptoms and 25 out of 180 staff members have reported suspected symptoms.

The Care Facility is at risk of a concentrated infection, and the CDC has sent a team to investigate and help. Health officials in Seattle and King County also said more than 50 people at the "Corcoran life-long Care Center" had been hospitalized with respiratory disease or pneumonia and were being tested for COVID-19, more positive cases are expected.

The COVID-19 is spreading around the world, cases are increasing in the United States, and 80 percent of cases are mild and don't even need to see a doctor, but some cases are very serious, local health officials said at a news conference.
